label.value: spindle pole body-nuclear membrane anchor activity

value.value: The binding activity of a molecule that brings together a mitotic spindle pole body and the nuclear membrane, in order to maintain specific membrane location of the spindle pole body.

label.value: cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane, cell tip

value.value: The leaflet the plasma membrane at the cell tip that faces the cytoplasm and any proteins embedded or anchored in it or attached to its surface.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of culmorin, a sesquiterpenoid fungal metabolite and mycotoxin produced by some ascomycete species such as Fusarium culmorum, F. graminearum, F. venenatum and Leptosphaeria oraemaris.
Catalysis of the reaction: 5-diphospho-1D-myo-inositol 1,3,4,6-tetrakisphosphate + H2O = 1D-myo-inositol 1,3,4,5,6-pentakisphosphate + H+ + phosphate.

label.value: centromere detachment from spindle pole body involved in meiotic chromosome organization

value.value: The cell cycle process in which centromeres dissociate from the spindle pole body, contributing to the rearrangement of chromosomes into the orientation characteristic of meiotic prophase I.

label.value: kinetochore disassembly involved in meiotic chromosome organization

value.value: The cell cycle process in which outer kinetochore components delocalize from the centromere, contributing to the rearrangement of chromosomes into the orientation characteristic of meiotic prophase I.

label.value: regulation of vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus.

label.value: negative regulation of vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vesicle fustion with Golgi apparatus.

label.value: positive regulation of vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vesicle fusion with Golgi apparatus.
The process whereby a cytosine in a tRNA is methylated at position 3 of the cytosine.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of the exopolysaccharide galactosaminogalactan. GAG is a heteropolysaccharide composed of alpha-1,4 linked galactose, N-acetyl galactosamine (GalNAc) and galactosamine (GalN).
Binding to and responding, e.g. by conformational change, to changes in the cellular level of zinc.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of pyrocyanin, an iminium betaine that is 5-methylphenazin-5-ium which is substituted at position 1 by an oxidanidyl group.
